page.content: { 19:}This old SCOTS PINE, with its distinctive orange trunk, has produced the young trees nearby. The SCOTS is Britain's only native Pine and can be compared with the MONTEREY PINES' dark, deeply fissured trunks. { 20:}LAUREL is not a native shrub, being similar to RHODODENDRON in appearance, but with small white spikes of flowers and black fruits. On the left is a line of WESTERN RED CEDAR. { 21:}ASH regenerates well from wind dispearsed seeds where there is sufficient light. It has been underplanted here with shade-tolerant WESTERN HEMLOCKS. { 22:}Many WOODLAND FLOWERS can be seen along this path and SPECKLED WOOD BUTTERFLIES occur in Summer. The slope down to the car park was cleared in 1968.
